<article>
  <span class="badge badge-warning">THROWS</span>
  <h2>4. TrustedHTML Breaks Current unsafeHTML</h2>

  <div class="csp-indicator csp-on">
    ● Trusted Types: ON — <code>require-trusted-types-for 'script'; trusted-types dompurify lit-html</code>
  </div>

  <p>
    The natural "fix" might be: use DOMPurify with <code>RETURN_TRUSTED_TYPE: true</code>
    to get a <code>TrustedHTML</code> object, then pass it to <code>unsafeHTML()</code>.
    This would prove that the value was sanitized before rendering.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>But it throws.</strong> The current directive explicitly checks
    <code>typeof value !== 'string'</code> and throws an error for non-string inputs.
    <code>TrustedHTML</code> objects are not strings.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-block-label">unsafe-html.ts:38–43 — the type guard</div>
    <pre><code class="language-javascript">if (typeof value != 'string') {
  throw new Error(
    `${this.constructor.directiveName}() called with a non-string value`
  );
}</code></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-block-label">demo-4.js — what you're running</div>
    <pre><code class="language-javascript">import { html, render } from 'lit-html';
import { unsafeHTML } from 'lit-html/directives/unsafe-html.js';
import DOMPurify from '/js/dompurify.js';

const userInput = `&lt;img src=x onerror="alert('XSS!')"&gt; Hello!`;

// Get a TrustedHTML object — this is the "right" way to use Trusted Types
const trustedHtml = DOMPurify.sanitize(userInput, { RETURN_TRUSTED_TYPE: true });
console.log('Is TrustedHTML:', window.trustedTypes?.isHTML(trustedHtml)); // true

// This throws: "unsafeHTML() called with a non-string value"
render(
  html`&lt;div&gt;${unsafeHTML(trustedHtml)}&lt;/div&gt;`,
  document.querySelector('#result')
);</code></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="demo-area">
    <h3>Interactive Demo</h3>
    <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:#546e7a;margin-top:0">
      Check the DevTools console for the error message.
    </p>
    <button class="run-btn" id="run-btn">Run Demo</button>
    <div class="result-box" id="result">
      <em style="color:#999">Output will appear here after clicking "Run Demo".</em>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p style="margin-top:1.5rem">
    So there's no way to use <code>unsafeHTML()</code> correctly with Trusted Types:
    passing a raw string bypasses enforcement; passing <code>TrustedHTML</code> throws.
    The next page shows the proposed fix.
  </p>

